\par }{\plain \lang1033 Q:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 I am having problems trying to get the }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 program to work on my GUS.  It's a Windows MOD player, and I have never had problems with Windows based programs before.  I}{\plain \lang1033 
t locks for me when I try to switch to 16 bit mode in any frequency other than 11 kHz.  I believe the WIN drivers for the GUS only support certain frequencies with 16 bit.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 A:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Many problems turn out to be caused by the wave driver, the sound card itself, or certain system setups.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 In general, }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  does not depend on any hardware specific properties.  Unless you use it in }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  mode, it strictly uses the }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 wave driver interface}{\plain \lang1033 
 for the sound output and should therefore work just fine with any setup that claims to support MPC-2.  In practice however, we still find an occasional problem with some systems.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Q:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 My }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 system freezes}{\plain \lang1033  when I try to play }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 A:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 This problem should be solved with our newer releases.  The problem here was neither }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 nor your sound card, but your card's wave driver.  Many wave drivers are still very buggy and don't perform up to specification.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 During the }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 Setup Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 SetupDlg}{\plain \lang1033  }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  asks t}{\plain \lang1033 
he wave driver if it is able to play at the selected settings.  The wave driver keeps answering "yes", but in fact supports only very few sample rates.  Since }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 doesn't know what kind of sound card it's running on, it takes this for granted and tries to play at these settings.  Then the wave driver suddenly decides not to play and hangs the system.  So to be correct, it's your wave driver and not }{\plain 
\lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  that causes your system to lock, but since }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  is the application that called the service of t}{\plain \lang1033 he wave driver, Windows will blame }{\plain \lang1033 
HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Starting at version 2.00 of }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
, we implemented a more stable approach to this problem by allowing wave drivers that appear to behave subnormal to select only the standard sample rates Windows supports, that is 11025, 22050, and 44100 kHz.  For more information on this topic see also }
{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Change Sample Rate in kHz Steps}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_ratech}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
