\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Q:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 I have been playing with }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 and I don't have a sound card yet, but I'm playing around to see what's available when I buy one.  I do have the PC-speaker driver installed and every time I try to play a MOD I get an annoying error message.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 I know I really can't get full capabilities w/o a sound card, but I'd like to try thi}{\plain \lang1033 s app. out because it seems pretty cool.  Any help would be appreciated.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 A:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 The error message you see is generated by the waveform sound driver you installed in your Control Panel, not by }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
.  We just put it in our own message box.  There is no way you could make }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  run with }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 speaker.drv}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 The }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 System Requirements}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 WhatUNeed}{\plain \lang1033  section in this help file says very clearly that you need an "asynchronous" wave driver, and that "}{\plain 
\b\lang1033 speaker.drv}{\plain \lang1033  cannot be supported".}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 In case you are i}{\plain \lang1033 nterested, let me explain it a little more technically:}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 requires an asynchronous wave driver, that means a wave driver, which can play sound by itself, without utilizing the CPU.  A wave driver that drives a sound card is asynchronous and works in the following way:  You point the driver to a certain memory l
}{\plain \lang1033 ocation and pass a number of parameters that describe the sound format, and the hardware will then read the data from the memory through its DMA (direct memory access) channel and play by it}{\plain \lang1033 self (simplified).}{\plain 
\lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 
The speaker driver cannot do this, because there is no hardware to handle the sound output.  The driver emulates a DAC (digital-analog converter), but does this through massive utilization of the CPU, that means, while }{\plain \b\lang1033 speaker.drv}
{\plain \lang1033  plays a wave file, you can't do anything else on your computer.  Even if you have interrupts enabled, that means nothing else but that you can move the mouse and that your keyboard input will be placed in the message queue.}{\plain 
\lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  cannot support this, s}{\plain \lang1033 
ince it requires a lot of CPU time by itself for generating the sound in all the channels and mixing them together.  So eventually it had to stop the sound output to calculate more.  That doesn't make sense for a background MOD player.}{\plain \lang1033 

\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 So after all, you should consider getting a sound card.  If you get a card that is capable of 16 bit stereo playback at 44 kHz, you won't be disappointed by the quality of the sound that }{\plain \lang1033 
HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  produces.}{\plain \lang1033 
