\par }{\plain \lang1033 Q:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 My modules seem to }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 lose}{\plain \lang1033  some of the }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 high frequencies}{\plain \lang1033  when I use }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 IDO}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_IDO}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 A:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Yeah, that's the wh}{\plain \lang1033 
ole point.  Although it might sound better to you because you've gotten used to it, these high frequencies don't belong there.  They are the result of harmonics produced by the mixer routine and the lack of digital filters to remove them.  If the module u
}{\plain \lang1033 
ses samples of excellent quality, you shouldn't hear much difference between sampling with IDO and without, but if there is a difference I can assure you the way it sounds with IDO is how it was supposed to.  This becomes especially noticeable with some o
}{\plain \lang1033 ld}{\plain \lang1033 er modules in the original MOD format that use pretty poor quality samples.  Oversampling without IDO then produces some very nasty harmonics that can be heard as clinking throughout the module.}{\plain \lang1033 

