\par }{\plain \lang1033 Q:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 The }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 CPU meter keeps getting into the red range}{\plain \lang1033  on my machine, especially with more than 8 channels.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 A:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 
Yes, these high-channel modules put a high load on your processor.  Although the mixer routines in this release are once again faster than in the previous one, on slow processors you may still exceed you}{\plain \lang1033 
r machine's resources.  There are several ways to lower the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 CPU Load}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 main_percnt}{\plain \lang1033 , so you can still listen to your favorite modules:}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \fi-720\li720\tx450 {\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 1.}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Disable }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Panning}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_panning}{\plain \lang1033 
.  If the module uses panning, the panned channels are mixed into both, the left and the right output.  This adds considerably to the CPU load and is sometimes not that much of an improvement.  With panning disabled, the pan position for each channel will
}{\plain \lang1033  be set to left, middle, or right, depending on what's closest.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 2.}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Disable }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 IDO}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_IDO}{\plain \lang1033 
.  Although a great improvement for the listening experience, IDO will increase your CPU load dramatically, up to doubling it, depending on other factors.  Without IDO there will be more harmonics in the output stream, but in modules with high-quality sam
}{\plain \lang1033 ples and many channels this tends to be less noticeable anyway.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 3.}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Lower the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Sample Rate}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_sr}{\plain \lang1033 
:  Sample rate and CPU load are directly proportional, so by decreasing the sample rate you will always see a reduced CPU load.  Unfortunately, sample rate a}{\plain \lang1033 nd sound quality are directly proportional too.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Of course the best solution to this problem is }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \fi-450\li450\tx450 {\plain \lang1033 
