\par }{\plain \lang1033 Q:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Sometimes I hear these really }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 annoying scratchy sounds}{\plain \lang1033 .  I don't think that's been a problem in version 2.00.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 A:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 The module you're playing is over-amping, or in other words, the pre-amplification is set too high.  Use the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 PreAmp Slider}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 main_PreAmp}{\plain 
\lang1033  to reduce the value until the scratchy sounds disappear.  This is the optimal setting for this module.  You can also }{\plain \lang1033 enable }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Clipping}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_clip}{\plain \lang1033 
 to eliminate short periods of over-amping in some modules.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 It is important to understand that the PreAmp slider is }{\plain \b\lang1033 not a volume control}{\plain \lang1033 .  It's more like a }{\plain \b\lang1033 quality control}{\plain \lang1033 
.  You can use it to maximize the output quality (dynamics and SNR) by finding the highest value at which the module doesn't over-amp yet.  Unfortunately this value is different for every module, depending on the number of channels, the quality of the sam
}{\plain \lang1033 ples, and much more.  If you set the slider to 0 dB you s}{\plain \lang1033 hould never have a problem with over-amping in any modules and get a pretty good approximation for the optimal setting.  Clipping can be used to suppress the }
{\plain \b\lang1033 effects }{\plain \lang1033 of over-amping, while reducing the pre-amp value eliminates the }{\plain \b\lang1033 cause}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
