\par }{\plain \lang1033 Q:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 While I really like the sound quality of }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 , is it possible to }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 reduce the amount of memory}{\plain \lang1033 
 required by the program?  My system runs on 4 MB RAM only and I also wish to have other applications running at the same time.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 A:}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 The memory required to buffer the output data }{\plain \lang1033 is directly proportional to all of the following:}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 *}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 sample rate (11-48 kHz)}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 *}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 resolution (8/16 bit)}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 *}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 channels (mono/stereo)}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 *}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 number of buffers (2-99)}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 
The first 3 parameters directly influence the quality of the sample data.  Since you don't want to compromise the quality, you can only change the number of buffers to reduce the amount of memory needed.  Indeed there is a wide range to choose from: the m
}{\plain \lang1033 inimum is 2 buffers and the maximum is 99.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Buffers are needed because Windows doesn't g}{\plain \lang1033 uarantee an application to get processor time when needed.  Instead }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 depends on the kindness of other programs to give up the processor for a while.  When an application shows the hour glass, it doesn't want to give up the processor because it needs the full processor power for itself.  All other applications are then sus
}{\plain \lang1033 pended and have to wait for the one that ties up the CPU.  The same thing happens when a DOS session is run full screen.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Since you want to hear your MODs continuously, even when }{\plain \lang1033 an application shows the hour glass for a while, }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 calculates some song data ahead, just as much as fits into the buffers you reserved.  Even when }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 doesn't get CPU time, the asynchronous wave driver will continue to move song data from memory to your sound card.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 
The reason to have more buffers is to overcome longer periods without CPU attention.  One buffer is big enough to hold 200 ms of sample data.  So the total range is from 0.4 sec (with 2 buffers) to roughly 20 sec (with 99 buffers).}{\plain \lang1033 }
{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 
If you usually don't see the hour glass for more than a few seconds (or don't mind a little interruption in play back once in a while), you can safely decrease the number of buffers to whatever makes you feel comfortable in terms of memory utilization.  I
}{\plain \lang1033 t doesn't influence the play back quality.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Another way to reduce memory is by running }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  in }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Interrupt Mode}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_TInterrupt}{\plain \lang1033 
.  Then you can go down to the minimal amount of buffers because there's no need to buffer much data.  However, you'll nee}{\plain \lang1033 d a fast machine to achieve a comfortable multitasking behavior in this mode.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
