\par }\pard \qc\keepn \cbpat16 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # WhatIsMod}${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 $ What is a MOD-File?}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 K Modules; What is a MOD file?}+{\footnote 
\pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 + MODs: 010}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\cf2 What is a MOD-File?}{\fs28 
\par }\pard {\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \qj {\plain \lang1033 A MOD-File is a collection of }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 sample data }{\plain \lang1033 (similar to the WAVE format) and a }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 description}{\plain \lang1033 
 of how to play these samples (similar to the MIDI format).  The samples in a MOD-File are raw, 8 bit, signed, headerless, linear digital data.  There may be up to }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 31 distinct samples}{\plain \lang1033  in a MOD-File, each w}
{\plain \lang1033 
ith a length of up to 128K (though most are much smaller, about 10K - 60K).  The sequencing information in a MOD-File contains 4 tracks of information describing which, when, for how long, and at what frequency samples should be played.  This means that a
}{\plain \lang1033  MOD-File can have up to 31 distinct sampled sounds, with up to }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 4 playing simultaneously}{\plain \lang1033 
 at any given point.  This allows a wide variety of orchestrational possibilities.  15 instrument MODs are somewhat older than 31 instrument MODs and are not seen very o}{\plain \lang1033 ften anymore.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 The samples are called }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 instruments}{\plain \lang1033 
, but they don't necessarily have to be samples of real instruments.  It doesn't really matter if the sound of a violin, an exotic oriental instrument, a human voice, or the noise of crushing tomatoes is used as a sample.  The ability to use one's own sam
}{\plain \lang1033 ples as instruments is a flexibility that other music files/formats do not share, and is one of the reasons MOD-Files are so popular, numerous, and diverse.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 The description how to play these samples is d}{\plain \lang1033 ivided into so-called }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Patterns}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Pattern}{\plain \lang1033 .  Each of these }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 patterns }{\plain \lang1033 
contains exactly 64 note lines (divisions), that specify the play pitch and effects for each of the four channels.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Therefore the MOD format reveals a }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 big advantage}{\plain \lang1033 
 over the WAVE and MIDI format.  Any naturally recorded sound can be used as an instrument (what MIDI is only able to do on sound boards with wave table lookup and a special synthesizer chip like the Yamaha }{\plain \b\ul\cf11\lang1033 OPL4}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 opl4_mode}{\plain \lang1033 ).  Moreover these sounds can be played in any desired order an}{\plain \lang1033 
d with several effects.  This way, the amount of data is reduced to a fraction compared to a WAVE file that produces the same sound.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Of course, there are also some important }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 disadvantages}{\plain \lang1033 !  If played on regular sound boards with one or two channels, MOD-Files clink (}{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 Why is that?}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
ModIntern}{\plain \lang1033 ).  Samples are stored with only 8 bit resolution in the file, and the maximum possible sample frequency for a sample in a MOD-File is about 32 kHz., which makes CD quality impossible (that's no problem for WAVE and MID}
{\plain \lang1033 I files).}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
Another disadvantage is that the samples are only mono and the MOD-Player has to distribute them (somewhat arbitrarily) between left and right.  Therefore listening to a bass drum through head phones can become a cruel experience, since our ear is used to
}{\plain \lang1033  receive low frequencies from all directions and not only in one ear.  This problem has been resolved in two different ways.  The traditional ProTracker format was extended to support }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Panning}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
effekte_panning}{\plain \lang1033  and for those modules that don't, you}{\plain \lang1033  can play them with }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Surround Sound}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_surround}{\plain \lang1033 
.  Both methods greatly improve stereo playback to overcome this historic limitation.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Besides the regular ProTracker format described above, the dramatic evolution of sound cards and processor power for the PC has produced }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 many more powerful formats}{\plain \lang1033 
 in the last years.  There are modules now with up to 32 simultaneous channels, a maximum of 255 instruments, possible sample rates of up to 48 kHz, and 16 bit source samples of (almost) unlimited size.  Most of these }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Formats}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Info_Type}{\plain \lang1033  are also supported in }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  and some more will be supported in the future.}{\plain \lang1033 
