\par }{\plain \lang1033 The }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 MOD-Format}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Info_Type}{\plain \lang1033  originally comes from the }{\plain \b\lang1033 Commodore Amiga}{\plain \lang1033 
, that features a relatively intelligent sound chip, the PAULA.  This chip can play samples on four channels with different pitches (sample rates) and volumes at the same time.  That's why it is relatively simple to pass the PAULA a new pitch or volume va
}{\plain \lang1033 lue, or a new sample now and then, therefore an }{\plain \b\lang1033 Amiga }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 MOD}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 WhatIsMod}{\plain \lang1033 -Player uses a minimal amount of CPU power and plays almost by itself.}{\plain 
\lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 On a PC however we mostly deal with relatively }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 dumb sound cards}{\plain \lang1033 , that feature only one or two channels, which even ha}{\plain \lang1033 
ve to work at the same sample rate.  Therefore we are forced to mix the samples from the }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 MOD}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 WhatIsMod}{\plain \lang1033 
-Files together at a new sample rate.  That means sampling up or down, or to put it this way: we have to skip over some bytes, pack the rest together with other skipped bytes and pass the resulting pulp to the sound card.  Further complicating this is the
}{\plain \lang1033  missing volume control, which causes an immense loss of quality at low volumes.  These problems can only be compensated by 16 bit sampling.  In short, on a}{\plain \lang1033 
 PC we are forced to calculate some pulp, put it in relation to the volume and mix this all together.  That takes time!}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
The big problem with sampling is the art of playing a noise back just as it was recorded and as memory efficient as possible.  But because the original can only be sampled with a certain frequency, it is not useful to record bird chirps with a sample rate
}{\plain \lang1033  of 1 kHz for instance, because the chirps contain frequencies of up to 20 kHz and higher and you would only record an arbitrary seque}{\plain \lang1033 
nce of something.  In short, the signal has to be recorded to the memory in a way that it is reproducible, that means the original signal has to be modified in a way that the highest frequency in this signal is lower than half the sample frequency of the 
}{\plain \lang1033 sound card.  This is called the }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 sampling theorem}{\plain \lang1033 .  If this is not obeyed, it is very likely that the signal is not reproducible or in other words, it doesn't sound good.}{\plain \lang1033 

\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 The same problem exists for reproducing the signal with Digital-Analog Converters (D}{\plain \lang1033 
AC).  Because it doesn't know what to do between two bytes (or words) of a sample and simply holds the last output value constant until the next input arrives, it transforms our nice smooth input to rectangles.  The result is the creation of }{\plain 
\b\cf2\lang1033 unwanted frequencies}{\plain \lang1033  that can be very high and disturbing and annoying to the ear.  They are called }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 harmonics}{\plain \lang1033 
.  Harmonics can be filtered out from the signal with a low pass (Oversampling and Filtering), but that's a different problem!  For more information about filter}{\plain \lang1033 s see }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 Further projects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Further
}{\plain \lang1033 !}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 The sound cards in our PCs often have these kinds of filters integrated, but they are not intelligent enough to remove these harmonics and can't be expected to be either.  Considering the fact that in a }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 MOD}
{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 WhatIsMod}{\plain \lang1033 
-File, samples with different sample rates (up to a ratio of 1:8) have to be mixed together over one channel to the sample rate of the sound card, which filter frequency is the sound card supposed to use?  So the DAC doesn't produce harmonics intentionall
}{\plain \lang1033 y, but t}{\plain \lang1033 he MOD-Player passes these }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 rectangular deformed waves}{\plain \lang1033 , that contain harmonics below the filter frequency of the sound card to it, and that clinks!}{\plain \lang1033 

\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 The only solution for that problem would be the implementation of a }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 digital filter}{\plain \lang1033 
 in the MOD-Player that has a variable filter frequency, but using this filter takes either memory or computing power to an extent that is not usual in today's PCs.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 With the release of version 2.10 we introduced a revolutionary technique we call IDO}{\plain \lang1033 \'99}{\plain \lang1033  which stands for }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 Interpolated Dynamic Oversampling}{\plain \lang1033 
.  With IDO, harmonics introduced by the mixer routine are greatly reduced.  Instead of using the last value of a sample, IDO calculates an estimate of the missing value.  This method somewhat smoothes out the rectangular shaped output curve produced by s
}{\plain \lang1033 ampling without IDO.  Because of the immense number of calculations, IDO will use large amounts of CPU power when enabled.  But if you have the spare power, you will be reimbursed with a }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 
much more enjoyable listening experie}{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 nce}{\plain \lang1033 
.  A large portion of the clinking will be unnoticeable to the human ear.  IDO doesn't relinquish the necessity of digital filters, but it makes them less essential and is another step towards the perfect reproduction of digital music modules.}{\plain 
\lang1033 
\par }\pard \qc\keepn \cbpat16 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # d2d_mode}${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 $ Direct To Disk Recording}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 K Modules; Recording; Direct To Disk Recording}+
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 + MODs: 021}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\cf2 Direct To Disk Recording}{\plain \ul\cf2\lang1033 
\par }\pard \qj {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Direct To Disk Recording means that the mixed and processed output of }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  is not passed on to the wave driver to produce soun}{\plain \lang1033 
d but rather written to a wave file on your hard disk.  This is particularly useful in two cases.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 First, if you have a }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 slow machine }{\plain \lang1033 that can't handle maximal sampling quality (especially with }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 IDO}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_IDO}{\plain \lang1033 
 enabled) without exceeding your CPU resources, you can record the module to disk and then listen to it as a wave file which is much less CPU int}{\plain \lang1033 ensive.  }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 will take as much time as it needs to record a module to disk and doesn't suffer from processing limitations as is the case with real-time playback.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Second, if you would like to transfer modules to }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 digital audio storage media }{\plain \lang1033 
like DAT or audio CD, using direct to disk recording will completely eliminate all analog stages in the process.  You can record the module to disk and then transfer it digitally to the master.  This will result in better audio quality then the convention
}{\plain \lang1033 al process }{\plain \lang1033 of sending the module to a sound card and recording it from the analog source.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 To make a recording, simply select }{\plain \b\lang1033 Direct To Disk Recording }{\plain \lang1033 as the output device, using the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Wave Driver Button}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_bname} {\plain \lang1033  in the }
{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 Setup Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 SetupDlg}{\plain \lang1033 .  Before the recording starts, a }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 File Name Selection Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 RecordingDlg}{\plain \lang1033 
 will prompt you for the correct path and file name of your recording.  After the recording has started you can stop at any time, however, you will not be able to use any of the other play control functions (}{\plain \lang1033 
pause, fast forward, rewind, next, previous) or change any of the sampling parameters (sample rate, pre-amplification...).  In order to change these parameters or select another song you must first stop the recording.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 At a sample rate of 44.1 kHz, Direct To Disk Recording requires about }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 10 MB }{\plain \lang1033 of free storage space on your hard drive }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 for every minute }{\plain \lang1033 
of the recording.  Therefore, if the module you want to record runs for 4 minutes and 30 seconds, you should have at least 45 MB of free space available befo}{\plain \lang1033 re attempting a recording.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \qc\keepn \cbpat16 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # hardware_mode}${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 $ Direct Hardware Support}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 
K Modules; Direct Hardware Support; Hardware Support; OPL4 Mode; AudioTrix Pro; GF1 Mode; Gravis Ultrasound}+{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 + MODs: 022}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\cf2 Direct Hardware Support}{\plain \ul\cf2\lang1033 
\par }\pard \qj {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Direct hardware support is an alternative way to play modules if you have the necessary hardware.  It takes advantage of the enormous and powerful potential of modern }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 wavetable synthesizer chips}{\plain 
\lang1033 
.  The basic strategy behind direct hardware support is to upload the samples from the module to the onboard RAM of your sound card and then have the synthesizer chip mix the samples accordingly to the processed and interpreted sequencing data sent to the
}{\plain \lang1033  card in real-time.  This has the obvious advantage of }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 freeing your CPU }{\plain \lang1033 
from mixing the samples which takes most of the time in regular software mixing mode.  Most wavetable synthesizer chips have some kind of interpolation scheme already built in and yield}{\plain \lang1033 
 sound quality as good as or better than software mixing with }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 IDO}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_IDO}{\plain \lang1033 
, but at no extra cost in terms of CPU utilization.  In general, CPU utilization is very low in this mode and will rarely exceed 4% on a 486DX/50.  Another advantage of direct hardware support is that since the samples are uploaded to the onboard RAM of y
}{\plain \lang1033 our sound card, they won't take up any space in main memory.  Also, since direct hardware support works in real-time, no output buffers are necessary which further }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 lowers memory requi}{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 
rements}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 To use direct hardware support you need to have a sound card with one of the supported }{\plain \b\cf2\lang1033 wavetable synthesizer chips and onboard RAM}{\plain \lang1033 .  If }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 finds any such card(s) in your system you can select them as the output device, using the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Wave Driver Button}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_bname} {\plain \lang1033  in the }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 Setup Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
SetupDlg}{\plain \lang1033 .  Due to the nature of direct hardware support, you will not be able to change most of the sampling parameters in this mode.  In fact, the only parameters you can change are }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 BPM Speeds Enabled}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 main_bpm}{\plain \lang1033  and }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Pr}{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 e-Amplification}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_preamp}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Although direct hardware support is possible with a number of wavetable synthesizer chips, }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  currently only supports sound cards with the Yamaha }{\plain \b\ul\cf11\lang1033 OPL4}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 opl4_mode}{\plain \lang1033  chip and the various Gravis Ultrasound cards based on the }{\plain \b\ul\cf11\lang1033 GF1}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 gf1_mode}{\plain \lang1033  chip.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \ri3298 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # opl4_mode}${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 $ OPL4 Mode}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 OPL4 Mode}{\plain \ul\cf2\lang1033 
\par }\pard \qj\ri3298 {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 OPL4 mode is a }{\plain \b\uldb\cf11\lang1033 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033 
 mode that employs the Yamaha OPL4 wavetable synthesizer chip.  This mode requires that you have an OPL4 based sound card with onboard RAM.  The only such card currently available is the }{\plain \b\uldb\cf11\lang1033 AudioTrix Pro}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
Audiotrix}{\plain \lang1033  from MediaTrix.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\ul Note}: It is not enough to have an OPL4 based sound card (like the {\cf2 Logitech SoundMan Wave}) without onboard wavetable RAM.  HyperMOD will produce an error message if it finds an OPL4 synthesizer chip but no RAM.
\par {\ul 
\par }{\ul Restriction}: The OPL4 architecture doesn't support individual samples that exceed 64 KB in length.  If a module contains larger samples, HyperMOD
 will display a warning, but you can still play the module.  Also, the total length of all samples in the module can not exceed the amount of onboard wavetable RAM on your card.  HyperMOD
 will also produce a warning if it runs out of memory on your card, but lets you play the song.{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \ri3298 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # gf1_mode}${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 $ GF1 Mode}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 GF1 Mode (Gravis Ultrasound)}{\plain \ul\cf2\lang1033 
\par }\pard \qj\ri3298 {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 GF1 mode is a }{\plain \b\uldb\cf11\lang1033 Direct Hardware Suppor}{\plain \b\uldb\cf11\lang1033 t}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033 
 mode that employs the GF1 wavetable synthesizer chip.  This mode requires that you have a Gravis Ultrasound card (GUS, GUS Ace, or GUS Max) with onboard RAM.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\ul Note}: HyperMOD relies on your ULTRASND environment variable to find and detect the card.  Make sure your environment contains the correct settings for the card before you attempt to use GF1 mode.
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\ul Restriction}: The total length of all samples in the module can not exceed the amount of onboard wavetable RAM on your card (typically 512 or 1024 KB).  HyperMOD
 will display a warning if it runs out of memory on your card, but lets you play the song.{\plain \lang1033 
