\par }{\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_sr}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Sample Rate}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 displays the current sample rate.  Higher sample rates yield better sound quality, but also require more CPU power.  For instance 32 kHz means that }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  has to mix 32,000 samples per second.}
{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }On better sound boards HyperMOD is able to sample with up to 48 kHz, however 32 kHz are practically sufficient, since this is the highest frequency of any sample recorded in a regular {\uldb\cf11 MOD}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 whatismod}
-File and therefore also the highest quality.  Other {\ul\cf11 Module Formats}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Info_Type} however may benefit from a higher sample rate.
\par 
\par For comparison we show here the data of some digital devices:
