\par }
\par For more information about sample rate see also the section {\uldb\cf11 Frequently asked Questions (FAQ)}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 FAQ}.{\uldb 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_bits}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Sample Depth}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 determines the resolution of the sampled output.  It is preferable to select 16 bit output if you have enough memory at your disposal and your sound device is capable of 16 bit sampling.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }For regular 4-channel {\uldb\cf11 MOD}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 whatismod}
s there is not much of an audible difference between 8- and 16-bit playback, because the mixing only yields 9 or 10 bit output anyway.  However, as the number of channels increases, the advantage of 16 bit playback becomes more prevalent.
\par 
\par See also: {\ul\cf11 Bits per Sample}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Main_Bits}
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode this switch is locked at 16 bit.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_ms}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Mono/Stereo/Surround Switch}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 toggles the output between mono and stereo.  In stereo mode you can also choose }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Surround Sound}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_surround}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }See also: {\ul\cf11 Mono/Stereo/Surround Sound}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Main_MS}
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode this switch is locked at stereo.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_surround}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Surround Sound}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 If you use }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Stereo}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_ms}{\plain \lang1033  mode, you can also enable surround sound.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }The original {\uldb\cf11 MOD}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 whatismod}
-Format was designed to play each channel either only left or right.  (The good old AMIGA couldn't do any better.)  This is not a very pleasant listening experience, especially with head phones.  Using surround sound, each channel will be mixed into both,
 left and right output, delaying one side to produce a more realistic sound.
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: Using this option will increase the {\ul\cf11 CPU Usage}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Main_Percnt} in your system.  Also, modules that use the {\ul\cf11 Panning}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_panning} command may sound better with this option turned off.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_buffs}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Output Buffers}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 shows the number of buffers }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  uses to temporarily store the sample output.  }{\plain \cf2\lang1033 One buffer is enough to play for 200 milliseconds.}{\plain \cf2\lang1033 
\par }
\par {\b Buffers} are necessary, because under Windows\'99 it is uncertain when a task will get access to the CPU again.  Therefore we have to calculate a certain amount of output in advance that can then be played.
\par 
\par Use the {\ul\cf11 Output Buffers Button}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_bbuffs} to change the number of buffers.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_bbuffs}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Output Buffers Button}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 selects the number of }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Output Buffers}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_buffs}{\plain \lang1033 .  You can select any number between 2 and 99, that means buffering between 0.4 and 19.8 sec of sound.}{\plain \lang1033 

\par }
\par {\ul Note}: More buffers will increase the amount of {\ul\cf11 Memory}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_mem} needed by HyperMOD, however, in some {\ul\cf11 Timer Modes}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_TMode} this will also enhance the multitasking behavior of HyperMOD.
\par 
\par For more information about buffers see also the section {\uldb\cf11 Frequently asked Questions (FAQ)}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 FAQ}.{\uldb 
\par }
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode no buffers are necessary and this button is locked at 0 buffers.
\par {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_mem}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Minimal Memory}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 shows the memory in KBytes that is occupied by the selected number of }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Buffers}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_buffs}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
