\par }{\plain \lang1033 For the total amount of memory used you also have to consider the size of }{\plain \b\lang1033 mod4win.exe}{\plain \lang1033 , }{\plain \b\lang1033 player32.dll}{\plain \lang1033 , the }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 MOD}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
whatismod}{\plain \lang1033 -File that's playing, the system files of Windows}{\plain \lang1033 \'99}{\plain \lang1033 , and other applications that are running.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }
\par For more information about how to optimize memory requirements and sound quality see also the section {\uldb\cf11 Frequently asked Questions (FAQ)}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 FAQ}.{\uldb 
\par }
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode this display shows the amount of wavetable RAM found on your sound card.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_IDO}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 IDO}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 sets the default for IDO}{\plain \lang1033 \'99}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }Interpolated Dynamic Oversampling (IDO) is a method to interpolate samples such that {\uldb\cf11 Harmonics}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 ModIntern}
 introduced through the mixer routine are greatly reduced and the resulting sound quality is considerably enhanced.  Using this method you can achieve much better sound quality, comparable to audio devices that use hardware mixing.
\par 
\par On the downside, IDO requires large amounts of CPU power, your {\ul\cf11 CPU Utilization}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Main_Percnt} may double when using this feature.
\par 
\par You can also toggle IDO temporarily from within the {\uldb\cf11 Main Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 HauptDlg}.
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode this switch is disabled.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_panning}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Panning}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 sets the default for panning.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }Panning enabled means that a channel can be mixed into the left and the right output simultaneously with different volumes to create the impression of the instrument sitting somewhere between the speakers.  This requires more {\ul\cf11 CPU Time}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Main_Percnt} because a panned channel needs to be mixed twice, demanding more computations.  If you're short of CPU power you can switch panning off and gain some percent.
\par 
\par You can also toggle panning temporarily from within the {\uldb\cf11 Main Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 HauptDlg}.
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode panning is always enabled.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_PreAmp}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Pre-Amplification}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }
Pre-amplification is necessary, because without it high-channel modules appear to sound quieter than modules with less channels.  This is simply due to the fact that the chance of all channels operating near full amplitude decreases with the number of cha
nnels.  Therefore, the higher the number of channels, the more the module needs to be pre-amplified to achieve a somewhat balanced impression in loudness when listening.
\par 
\par Unfortunately, under certain circumstances pre-amplification could be too high and cause over-amping in the mixer.  This is the case when you notice a scratching sound that disappears when you enable {\ul\cf11 Clipping}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_clip}
 or reduce pre-amplification.
\par 
\par The default amount of pre-amplification is determined by the number of channels in the module or, in the case of {\b S3M}, by an internal variable in the module.  You can adjust the amount of pre-amplification during playback from within the {\uldb\cf11 
Main Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 HauptDlg} using the {\ul\cf11 PreAmp Slider}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Main_PreAmp}.
\par {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_clip}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Clip Mixer Output}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 selects whether}{\plain \lang1033  the mixer routine should clip to maximum amplitude in case of over-amping or not.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }
\par If your {\ul\cf11 Pre-Amplification}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_PreAmp}
 is set too high, the mixer output could become too large for the range of 8 or 16 bit respectively.  Without clipping this would cause overflows and become audible as very nasty clicks, scratches, and distortions.  To prevent this, the mixed output can b
e clipped to maximum amplitude.  When over-amping occurs, clipped output will cause only slight distortions that will be unnoticeable for the most part.  If you want the ultimate quality, you should disable clipping and adjust the {\ul\cf11 PreAmp Slider}
{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 main_PreAmp} to a low enough value that prevents over-amping.
\par 
\par You can also toggle clipping temporarily from within the {\uldb\cf11 Main Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 HauptDlg}.
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode this switch is disabled.
