\par {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_TMode}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Timer Mode}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Because Windows is a non-preemptive multitasking system, }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033 
 has to cooperate with the other applications in some way to allow for a fair sharing of CPU time.  Because a compromise has to be made, we offer you several settings to choose the one that fits your needs best:}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 There are three possible timer modes:}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 * }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Windows Timer}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Setup_TTimer}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 * }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 MM Task}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Setup_TTa}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 sk}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 * }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Interrupt}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 Setup_TInterrupt}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }
Every of these Timer Modes has advantages and disadvantages.  What's best for you depends on your machine and your working habits.  But don't worry, experiment with the settings a little bit, and you'll find out what's best.  You can change this setting a
t any time, even during playback of a song.
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: In {\uldb\cf11 Direct Hardware Support}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 hardware_mode}{\plain \lang1033  }mode this switch is locked at Interrupt mode.  In {\uldb\cf11 Direct To Disk Recording}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 d2d_mode} mode it is locked at Task mode.
\par {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_TTimer}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Windows Timer}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 In this mode, }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  will be sent a timer message from Windows in fixed intervals of time.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }When such a message arrives, HyperMOD
 gets control of the CPU, fills one buffer, and returns control to Windows.  This mode is the most stable and reliable one and the default setting.  The drawback however is, that under certain circumstances, such as when an application occupies the CPU fo
r a long time without returning control to Windows (you will see an hour glass then), or when a non-Windows application (DOS task) runs in full screen mode, Windows can't send the timer message, because it doesn't have control of the CPU.  In this case, 
HyperMOD will continue to play as long as the buffers last, then however the playback will stop.
\par {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_TTask}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Multimedia Task}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 In this mode, }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  is assigned its own, preemptively controlled task from Windows.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }A minimal application is running in the background that gives HyperMOD all its CPU time.  This mode allows for a very fair sharing of resources and good multitasking behavior, because Windows splits the CPU equally between HyperMOD
, DOS tasks (if any), and all other Windows applications.  However, Task Mode will not work if an application doesn't free the CPU for a long time (hour glass) or other applications are too CPU-intensive and don't give the Multimedia Task enough time, as 
it happens with full screen DOS applications.
\par {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # setup_TInterrupt}{\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Interrupt}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 In this mode, }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  will be activated through a hardware interrupt.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }This interrupt comes always, even when no timer message would be sent.  In this mode HyperMOD
 will keep playing, no matter what.  The problem here is that other applications will be interrupted regardless of what they are just doing.  This can be very dragging on these applications, especially when a new song is loaded and HyperMOD
 tries to fill the buffers as quickly as possible.  This mode is comfortable to work with if you have lots of CPU power (4DX/50 or better) and like to run non-Windows applications full screen.
\par 
\par {\ul Note}: On a slow machine this mode could be dangerous, because during the interrupt that HyperMOD
 uses to do its calculations, other interrupts may occur and compromise the stability of the complicated and sensitive Windows operating system which might lead to a Protection Fault Error and could sometimes crash the system.
\par {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_ratech}{\b\fs28\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Change Sample Rate in kHz Steps}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }\pard \ri3286\tx360 {\plain \lang1033 This setting determines how to the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Sample Rate}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_sr}{\plain \lang1033  is changed using the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Sample Rate Button}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 setup_bsr}
{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }Some sound drivers (like the one for the {\cf2 PAS 16}
) report being able to play any sample rate from 11 to 48 kHz.  Most others will report to support only the Windows specific (standard) sample rates 11025, 22050, and 44100 Hz.  At the default setting ({\b OFF}) HyperMOD
 will let you select only those sample rates the wave driver reports of being able to play.  However, some of the drivers that claim to support only the standard rates are able to play many others (like the driver for the {\cf2 AudioTrix Pro}
).  If you're convinced your driver is able to handle other rates, but HyperMOD doesn't let you select them, you can change the default setting (to {\b ON}), and HyperMOD will then allow you to select any sample rate in steps of 1 kHz.
\par 
\par {\ul Caution}: Some wave drivers (like the one for the {\cf2 Gravis Ultrasound}) will cause protection faults when you force them to other than the standard sample rates.  Use this option on your own risk!
\par \pard \ri3286 {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_pausesetup}{\b\fs28\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Pause Playback during Setup}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 This setting determines whether }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  will conti}{\plain \lang1033 nue playback when you open the Setup Dialog or not.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \ri3286\tx450 {\plain \lang1033 
\par }Because of the incompatibility problems with wave drivers, HyperMOD defaults ({\b ON}
 position) to pause any playing song when the Setup Dialog is opened.  During this dialog the wave driver is asked if it can handle certain settings.  Some wave drivers then immediately change their settings to these values, whether we want them or not.  
HyperMOD however will continue to calculate the sound at the old settings and produce very unpleasant distortions.  Unfortunately there is no way for HyperMOD
 to tell if your wave driver handles these queries correctly or not.  If you have a wave driver that behaves correctly (such as {\cf2 PAS 16}, {\cf2 AudioTrix Pro}, {\cf2 Gravis Ultrasound}) , you can change this setting to {\b OFF}.  HyperMOD
 will then continue playing when you open the Setup Dialog.
\par \pard \ri3286 {\plain \lang1033 \page }#{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # setup_playonload}{\b\fs28\cf2  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Automatic Playback after Open}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 In the default setting (}{\plain \b\lang1033 ON}{\plain \lang1033 ) }{\plain \lang1033 HyperMOD}{\plain \lang1033  will immediately start playing the current selection from the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Playlist}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
open_playlist}{\plain \lang1033  after you load files through the }{\plain \uldb\cf11\lang1033 Open Dialog}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 OpenDlg}{\plain \lang1033 , pass command line parameters, or use }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Drag & Drop}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 dragdrop}
