\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_setftune}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Set Finetune}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Where [14][5][x] means "sets the finetune value of the}{\plain \lang1033  current sample to the signed nibble x".  x has legal values of 0..15, corresponding to signed nibbles 0..7,-8..-1.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_ploop}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Pattern Loop}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
Where [14][6][x] means "set the start of a loop to this division if x is 0, otherwise after this division, jump back to the start of a loop and play it another x times before continuing".  If the start of the loop was not set, it will default to the start
}{\plain \lang1033  of the current pattern.  Hence 'loop pattern' cannot be p}{\plain \lang1033 erformed across multiple patterns.  Note that loops do not support nesting, and you may generate an infinite loop if you try to nest 'loop pattern's.}{\plain 
\lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_tremwave}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Set Tremolo Waveform}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Where [14][7][x] means "set the waveform of succeeding }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Tremolo}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_tremolo}{\plain \lang1033  effects to wave #x".  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Set Vibrato Waveform}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_vibwave}{\plain \lang1033 , but alters the 'tremolo' effect.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_panning2}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Set Panning}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Where [14][8][x] means "distribute the sample in this channel, such that x/15 of it are mixed }{\plain \lang1033 into the right output and the rest into the left".  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Set Panning}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
effekte_panning}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_retrignote}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Retrigger Note}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
Where [14][9][x] means "trigger current sample every x ticks in this division".  If x is 0, then no retriggering is done (acts as if no effect was chosen), otherwise the retriggering begins on the first tick and then x ticks after that, etc.}{\plain 
\lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_fvup}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Volume Up}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Where [14][10][x] means "increment the volume of the current sample by x".  The incrementing takes place at the beginning of the division, and hence there is no sliding.  You cannot slide beyond volume 64.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_fvdn}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Volume Down}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Where [14][11][x] means "decrement the volume of the current sample by x".  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Fine Volume Up}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_fvup}{\plain \lang1033  but lowers the volume. You cannot slide beyond volume 0.}
{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_cutnote}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Note Cut}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Where [14][12][x] means "after the current sample has been played for x ticks in this division, its volume will be set to 0".  This implies that if x is 0, then you will not hear any of the sample.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_notedelay}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Note Delay}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
Where [14][13][x] means "do not start this division's sample for the first x ticks in this division, play the sample after this".  This implies that if x is 0, then you will hear no delay.  Note that this effect only influences a sample if it was started 
}{\plain \lang1033 in this division.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_pdelay}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Pattern Delay}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
Where [14][14][x] means "after this division there will be a delay equivalent to the time taken to play x divisions after which the pattern will be resumed".  The delay only relates to the interpreting of new divisions, and all effects and previous notes 
}{\plain \lang1033 continue during delay.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_invloop} {\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Invert Loop}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Where [14][15][x] means "if x is greater than 0, then play the current sample's loop upside down at speed x".  Each byte in the sample's loop will have its sign changed (negated).}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }This effect is currently not supported by HyperMOD.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKT}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Oktalyzer Effects}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 These effects are only available in Oktalyzer modules in addition to some of the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Standard Effects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_standard}{\plain \lang1033  and a few of the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 
ProTracker Effects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_PT}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKTarp1}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Arpeggio 1}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Play note, note-x semitones, note, and n}{\plain \lang1033 ote+y semitones, then return to original note.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Arpeggio}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_arpg}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKTarp2}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Arpeggio 2}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Play note, note+x semitones, note, and note-y semitones, then return to original note.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Arpeggio}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_arpg}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKTtpup}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Tone Up}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Decrease the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Period of the Current Sample}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 sample_period}{\plain \lang1033  in semitone steps during the division with the speed X.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Portamento Up}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_pup}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKTtpdn}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Tone Down}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Increase the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Period of the Current Sample}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 sample_period}{\plain \lang1033  in semitone steps during the division with the speed X.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Portamento Down}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_pdn}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKTtpup1}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Tone Higher}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Decrease the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Period of the Current Sample}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 sample_period}{\plain \lang1033  by X at the beginning of the division.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Fine Portamento Up}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
effekte_fpup}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKTtpdn1}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Tone Lower}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Increase the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Period of the Current Sample}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 sample_period}{\plain \lang1033  by X at the beginning of the division.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Fine Portamento Down}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
effekte_fpdn}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_OKToldvol}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Old Volume}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Return the volume to its value before the last }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Set Volume}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_setvol}{\plain \lang1033  effect.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3M}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 ScreamTracker Effects}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 These effects are only available in ScreamTracker and FastTracker II modules in addition to all of the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Standard Effects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_standard}{\plain \lang1033  and the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 
ProTracker Effects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_PT}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mtremor}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Tremor (STM/S3M)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Periodically set the current sample's volume to 0 after X ticks in the division and then restore the previous value after another Y ticks in the division.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mexfpup}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Extra Fine Portamento Up (STM/S3M)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Decrement the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Period of the Current Sample}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 sample_period}{\plain \lang1033  by 1/4*Y.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Fine Portamento Up}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_fpup}{\plain \lang1033 
, but four times more accurate.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mexfpdn}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Extra Fine Portamento Down (STM/S3M)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Decrement the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Period of the Current Sample}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 sample_period}{\plain \lang1033  by 1/4*Y.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Fine Portamento Down}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_fpdn}{\plain \lang1033 
, but four times more accurate.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mretrigvolsld}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Retrigger + Volume Slide (S3M only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Perform a }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Retrigger Note}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_retr}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 ignote}{\plain \lang1033  with parameter Y and additionally apply a }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Volume Slide}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_volsld}
{\plain \lang1033  for each retriggered note.  The amount of the slide is determined by the parameter X.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mstereocontrol}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Stereo Control (S3M only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 This command changes the mixing mode for the channel. The mixing mode tells at what volume the channel is mixed to left and right output.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }This effect is no longer supported in later revisions of the ScreamTracker.  However, if you have any modules that contain this effect or if you want to use it in your own productions, HyperMOD will reproduce it correctly.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mglobalvol}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Set Global Volume (S3M only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Set the global volume to the given value.  This effects all channels in addition to the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Set Volume}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_setvol}{\plain \lang1033  effect for a single channel.  Legal volumes are 0..64.}
{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mbpmspeed}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Set BPM-Speed (S3M only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Set the}{\plain \lang1033  BPM-speed (tempo) to the given value.  This effect is similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Set Speed}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_setspeed}{\plain \lang1033 
, but it always sets the BPM-speed (tempo).  Legal tempos are 32..255.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }ScreamTracker implements two commands to set the speed and tempo since both, ticks/division and beats/minute may have values greater 31.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_S3Mfinevibr}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Vibrato (S3M only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Vibrate the current note with speed X and depth Y.  Similar to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Vibrato}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_vib}{\plain \lang1033 , but four times more accurate.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_669}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 669 and UNIS 699 Effects}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 These effects are only available in UNIS (extended) 669 and partly in FastTracker II modules.  They are provided in addition to some of the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Standard Effects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_standard}{\plain \lang1033 .
}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_669frequadjust}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Frequency Adjust(669 only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 Uses a slightly higher pitch for this note, depending on the parameter.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }This effect can be used to create flanging effects.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_669finepanleft}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Panning Left (UNIS and FT II only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 Shift the current pan position one notch to the left.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }There are 16 different pan position in UNIS 669.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_669finepanright}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Panning Right (UNIS and FT II only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 Shift the current pan position one notch to the right.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }There are 16 different pan position in UNIS 669.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_669slotretrigger}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Slot Retrigger (UNIS only)}
\par {\plain \lang1033 This command rapidly fires 4 slots.  The command parameter specifies the speed at which to do it.  The speed difference across the values is exponential.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }HyperMOD can only approximate this effect because there is no exact definition available on what exponential speed difference means.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FAR}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Farandole Composer Effects}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 These effects are only available in Farandole modules.  They are provided in addition to }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Set Speed}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_setspeed}{\plain \lang1033 , }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Set Panning}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 
effekte_panning2}{\plain \lang1033 , and }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Note Cut}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_cutnote}{\plain \lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARspecial}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Farandole Special Commands}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 This is a group of five sub-commands:}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \fi-180\li180\ri3286 {\plain \lang1033 *}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Turn Volume Ramp Wait Off/On}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 *}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Allow Loop Fulfillment}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 *}{\plain \lang1033 \tab }{\plain \lang1033 Use Modified/Standard FAR Tempos}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \ri3286 {\plain \lang1033 
\par }HyperMOD does not interpret any of these commands.  {\b Volume Ramp Wait }is only used internally by the Farandole composer, {\b Loop Fulfillment }is not supported by HyperMOD, and {\b Standard Tempos }are the default.
\par \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARfinepitchup}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Pitch Up}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Increase the pitch immediately by the given parameter.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARfinepitchdown}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Pitch Down}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Decrease the pitch immediately by the given parameter.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARnoteportamento}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Note Portamento}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Slide from the}{\plain \lang1033  current pitch to the pitch specified on the line where the command is issued.  The parameter tells in how many rows the pitch should have gotten to the destination.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARretrigger}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Retrigger}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Repeat the current note X times in this division.  If a drum is issued as the note and the parameter is 2 then the drum should be played 2 times during that division, in evenly spaced intervals.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARvibratodepth}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Vibrato Depth}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Set the depth for the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Vibrato Note}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_FARvibratonote}{\plain \lang1033  and }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Vibrato Sustained}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_FARvibratosust}{\plain \lang1033  effects.}
{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARvibratonote}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Vibrato Note}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Vibrato this note.  Although it goes away if you stop using it, this effect when used repeatedly actually just tells FAR to continue the previous vibrato, which may span several notes depending on how large it is.}{\plain \lang1033 

\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARvolslideup}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Volume Slide Up}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Increases the volume one notch.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }There are only 16 different volumes defined in FAR.{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARvolslidedown}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Volume Slide Down}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Decreases the vo}{\plain \lang1033 lume one notch.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }There are only 16 different volumes defined in FAR.{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARvibratosust}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Vibrato Sustained}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Is the same as }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Vibrato Note}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_FARvibratonote}{\plain \lang1033 , but it doesn't stop until another Vibrato Sustained with parameter 0 is given.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARvolumeportamento}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Volume Portamento}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 This uses the same method as the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Note Portamento}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_FARnoteportamento}{\plain \lang1033  command, but it acts on the volume.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARfinetempodown}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Tempo Down}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Slightly decreases the FAR tempo.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }In HyperMOD this is realized by changing the BPM-speed.{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s2 \fs20\lang1031 # effekte_FARfinetempoup}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Fine Tempo Up}
\par {\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Slightly increases the FAR tempo.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }In HyperMOD this is realized by changing the BPM-speed.{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\pard \ri3969 \page {\cf2 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # effekte_XM}}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 FastTracker II Effects}{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 These effects are only available in FastTracker II modules in addition to all of the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Standard Effects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_standard}{\plain \lang1033 , the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 ProTracker Effects}{
\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_PT}{\plain \lang1033 , and the }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 ScreamTracker Effects}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_S3M}{\plain \f3\lang1033 .}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page {\cf2 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # effekte_GlobVolSld}}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Global Volume Slide}{\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Performs a }{\plain \ul\cf11\lang1033 Volume Slide}{\v\f2\fs16\cf5 effekte_volsld}{\plain \lang1033  on all channels at once.}{\plain \lang1033 
\par }\page {\cf2 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \fs20\lang1033 # effekte_SetEnvPos}}{\plain \cf2\lang1033  }{\b\fs28\ul\cf2 Envelope Position}{\cf2 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 
\par }{\plain \lang1033 Sets the total position of the current instrument's envelopes.}{\plain \lang1033 
